<section xml:id="sec_inference">
  <title>Excursion: Equivalence and Inference</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Logical equivalences such as Demorgan's laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/> and the broken promise <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"/> help us negate statements,
      which is useful for constructing counterexamples to false statements,
      for writing proofs by contradiction,
      and for stating the contrapositive.
      The contrapositive equivalence <xref ref="thm_cp"/> and implication equivalence <xref ref="thm_implication"/> gave us new proof formats for proving conditionals and
      <q>or</q>
      statements, respectively.
      Logical equivalences can also help simplify complicated compound statements,
      which has applications to computer science.
      In this section,
      we return to discuss logical equivalences in more detail and also introduce logical inference.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_logical_equiv">
    <title>\subequiv</title>
    <p>
      In this section,
      we look at a long list of logical equivalences and see how to derive new logical equivalences from this list.
      We begin by introducing some new logical equivalences involving negations,
      tautologies, and contradictions.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_obvious_logical_equivalences">
      <title>Equivalences involving negations, tautologies, and contradictions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any logical statement <m>P</m>,
          tautology <c>T</c>,
          and contradiction <c>F</c>,
          we have the following logical equivalences.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_idem">
              <p>
                <term>Idempotent</term><fn>
                The word
                <q>idempotent</q>
                comes from the roots
                <q>idem</q>
                meaning self
                (as in the word
                <q>identity</q>
                )
                and
                <q>potent</q>
                meaning power
                (in the normal English sense, as in
                <q>omnipotent</q>
                )
                but used in mathematics to mean raised to an exponent.
                The word
                <q>idempotent</q>
                means the object equals its own power.
                </fn>
                <me>
                  P \land P \equiv P\text{ and } P \lor P \equiv P
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_id">
              <p>
                <term>Identity</term>
                <me>
                  P \land \str{T} \equiv P\text{ and } P \lor \str{F} \equiv P
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_dom">
              <p>
                <term>Domination</term>
                <me>
                  P \lor \str{T} \equiv \str{T}\text{ and } P \land \str{F}  \equiv \str{F}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_neg">
              <p>
                <term>Negation</term>
                <me>
                  P \lor \neg P \equiv \str{T}\text{ and } P \land \neg P \equiv \str{F}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_doubleneg">
              <p>
                <term>Double negation</term>
                <me>
                  \neg (\neg P) \equiv P
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      These logical equivalences can be confirmed using a truth table,
      but they should also make sense.
      Let's look closely at a couple of these equivalences.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_understand_equiv_negTF">
      <title>Understanding logical equivalences: negation, tautology, and contradiction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each equivalence from <xref ref="thm_obvious_logical_equivalences"></xref>,
          explain words why it is true.
          Recall that by <xref ref="defn_logical_equiv"></xref>
          that two statements are logical equivalent if they have the same truth values and so we can check if one statement is true,
          then so is the other and if one statement is false, then so is the other.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>P \lor P \equiv P</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    If <m>P \lor P</m> is true, then either <m>P</m> is true or <m>P</m> is true.
                    In either case, <m>P</m> is true.
                    If <m>P \lor P</m> is false, then <m>P</m> is false and <m>P</m> is false.
                    (We used Demorgan's laws, <xref ref="thm_demorgans"></xref> to negate the
                    <q>or</q>.)
                    In either case <m>P</m> is false.
                    Thus, <m>P \lor P \equiv P</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\neg (\neg P) \equiv P</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    If <m>\neg (\neg P)</m> is true,
                    then by definition of negation <xref ref="defn_negation_tautology_contradiction"/> <m>\neg P</m> is false and so <m>P</m> is true.
                    If <m>\neg (\neg P)</m> is false,
                    then by definition of negation <xref ref="defn_negation_tautology_contradiction"/> <m>\neg P</m> is true and so <m>P</m> is false.
                    Thus, <m>\neg (\neg P) \equiv P</m>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>P \land \str{F} \equiv \str{F}</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    For the statement <m>P \land \str{F}</m> to be true,
                    we would need both <m>P</m> and <m>\str{F}</m> to be true.
                    But <m>\str{F}</m> is a contradiction so it is always false.
                    Therefore <m>P \land \str{F}</m> is also always false.
                    That is, <m>P \land \str{F} \equiv \str{F}</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      The equivalence in <xref ref="defn_logical_equiv"></xref>
      <xref ref="part_equiv_distributive"/>, for example,
      is one of several equivalences that have names that may be familiar since we used the same names in integer algebra <xref ref="defn_integer_algebra_order_operations"/>.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_logical_equiv_comm_assoc_dist">
      <title>Commutative, associative, and distributive equivalences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any logical statements <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>,
          and <m>R</m>, we have the following logical equivalences.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_comm">
              <p>
                <term>Commutative property</term>
                <me>
                  P \land Q \equiv Q \land P
                </me>
                <me>
                  P \lor Q \equiv Q \lor P
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_assoc">
              <p>
                <term>Associative property</term>
                <me>
                  P \land (Q \land R) \equiv (P \land Q) \land R
                </me>
                <me>
                  P \lor (Q \lor R) \equiv (P \lor Q) \lor R
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_dist">
              <p>
                <term>Distributive property</term>
                <me>
                  P \land (Q \lor R) \equiv (P \land Q) \lor (P \land R)
                </me>
                <me>
                  P \lor (Q \land R) \equiv (P \lor Q) \land (P \lor R)
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Each of the statements in <xref ref="thm_logical_equiv_comm_assoc_dist"></xref>
      can be confirmed using a truth table.
    </p>
    <p>
      For reference,
      we repeat the implication and contraposition logical equivalences here.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_equiv_implication_cp__again">
      <title>Implication and contraposition equivalences, revisited</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For statements <m>P</m>,
          <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>, we have the following equivalences.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_impl">
              <p>
                <term>Implication</term> <xref ref="thm_implication"/>
                <me>
                  P \to Q \equiv \neg P \lor Q
                </me>
                <me>
                  R \lor Q \equiv \neg R \to Q
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_cp">
              <p>
                <term>Contraposition</term> <xref ref="thm_cp"/>
                <me>
                  (P \to Q) \equiv (\neg Q \to \neg P)
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We also repeat the equivalences that help us negate compound statements.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_equiv_neg_and_or_ifthen">
      <title>Negating compound statements, revisited</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
          we have the following equivalences.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>DeMorgan's laws</term>  <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/>
                <me>
                  \neg(P \land Q) \equiv \neg P \lor \neg Q
                </me>
                <me>
                  \neg(P \lor Q) \equiv \neg P \land \neg Q
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <term>Broken promise</term> <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"/>
                <me>
                  \neg(P \to Q) \equiv P \land \neg Q
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We can use this long list of equivalences to prove new equivalences.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_proof_logical_equiv">
      <title>Proofs of Logical Equivalences</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_fillinblankproof_cpequiv">
            <p>
              Many lists of equivalences omit contraposition because it can be proved from the other equivalences.
              Fill in the missing equivalences in <xref ref="tab_fillinblankproof_cpequiv"></xref> to prove contraposition.
              <table xml:id="tab_fillinblankproof_cpequiv">
                <title>Fill in the blanks to prove the contraposition equivalence <xref ref="act_proof_logical_equiv">for</xref> <xref ref="part_fillinblankproof_cpequiv"/></title>
                <tabular>
                  <row>
                    <cell><em>Proof:</em></cell>
                    <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\neg P \lor Q</m></cell>
                    <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>Q \lor \neg P</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\neg (\neg Q) \lor \neg P</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em> <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
                  </row>
                </tabular>
              </table>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand">
            <p>
              Fill in the missing steps of the proof in <xref ref="tab_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand"></xref> using the equivalences given.
              What new equivalence did we just prove?
              <table xml:id="tab_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand">
                <title>Fill in the blanks to expand <m>P \to (Q \land R)</m> <xref ref="act_proof_logical_equiv">for</xref> <xref ref="part_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand"/></title>
                <tabular>
                  <row>
                    <cell><em>Proof:</em></cell>
                    <cell><m>P \to (Q \land R)</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
                    <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                    <cell>using implication</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using the distributive property</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using implication (twice) <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
                  </row>
                </tabular>
              </table>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_proof_mp_using_equiv">
            <p>
              Fill in the missing equivalences in <xref ref="table_equiv_proof_mp"></xref>
              to prove <m>((P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q) \equiv \str{T}</m>.
              This tautology that shows that <em>modus ponens</em>
              (which we will see in <xref ref="thm_logical_infer"></xref>
              <xref ref="part_thm_infer_mp"/> is valid.
              <table xml:id="table_equiv_proof_mp">
                <title>Using equivalences to prove <em>modus ponens</em> is valid <xref ref="act_proof_logical_equiv">for</xref> <xref ref="part_proof_mp_using_equiv"/></title>
                <tabular>
                  <row>
                    <cell><em>Proof:</em></cell>
                    <cell><m>(P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(P \land (\neg P \lor Q)) \to Q</m></cell>
                    <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>((P \land \neg P) \lor (P \land Q)) \to Q</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(\str{F} \lor (P \land Q)) \to Q</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(P \land Q) \to Q</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\neg(P \land Q) \lor Q</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>(\neg P \lor \neg Q) \lor Q</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\neg P \lor (\neg Q \lor Q)</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\neg P \lor \str{T}</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em></cell>
                  </row>
                  <row>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\str{T}</m></cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                    <cell>using <em>\hspace{.75in}</em> <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
                  </row>
                </tabular>
              </table>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Make sure to <xref ref="act_proof_logical_equiv">complete</xref>
      because we are about to reveal some of the answers.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_proof_logical_equiv">
      <title>Proofs of Logical Equivalences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_fillinblankproof_cpequiv_answers">
              <p>
                Many lists of equivalences omit contraposition because it can be proved from the other equivalences.
                Fill in the missing equivalences in <xref ref="tab_fillinblankproof_cpequiv"></xref> to prove contraposition.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="tab_fillinblankproof_cpequiv_answers">See</xref>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="tab_fillinblankproof_cpequiv_answers">
                  <title>Using equivalences to prove the contraposition equivalence <xref ref="exam_proof_logical_equiv">for</xref> <xref ref="part_fillinblankproof_cpequiv_answers"/></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><em>Proof:</em></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg P \lor Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                      <cell>using implication</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q \lor \neg P</m></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>using the commutative property</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg (\neg Q) \lor \neg P</m></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>using double negation</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>using implication <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand_equiv">
              <p>
                Fill in the missing steps of the proof in <xref ref="tab_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand"></xref> using the equivalences given.
                What new equivalence did we just prove?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="tab_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand_answers">See</xref>.
                    We just proved a new equivalence:
                    <me>
                      P \to (Q \land R) \equiv (P \to Q) \land (P \to R)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="tab_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand_answers">
                  <title>Using equivalences to expand mathinlined4ce7bb95e50f26575f4d123af009e967f8d654<xref ref="exam_proof_logical_equiv">fENDfor</xref> <xref ref="part_fillinblanksproof_ifthenand"/></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><em>Proof.</em></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \to (Q \land R)</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg P \lor (Q \land R)</m></cell>
                      <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                      <cell>using implication</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>(\neg P \lor Q) \land (\neg P \lor R)</m></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>using the distributive property</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>(P \to Q) \land (P \to R)</m></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>using implication (twice) <nbsp/>  <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_simplify_neg">
    <title>\subneg</title>
    <p>
      We can use logical equivalences to simplify the negation of a statement.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_neg_complicated">
      <title>Negating a complicated statement</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Negate the statement
          <me>
            (P \lor R) \land (Q \lor\neg R)
          </me>
          and simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
          State which equivalences you use.
        </p>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We simplify the negation in <xref ref="tab_neg_complicated"></xref>.
          </p>
        </solution>
        <table xml:id="tab_neg_complicated">
          <title>Using equivalences to negate the complicated statement from <xref ref="exam_neg_complicated"></xref></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\neg ((P \lor R) \land (Q \lor \neg R))</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\neg (P \lor R) \lor \neg (Q \lor \neg R)</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>using De Morgan's laws</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(\neg P \land \neg R) \lor (\neg Q \land \neg (\neg R))</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>using De Morgan's laws (twice)</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(\neg P \lor \neg R) \land (\neg Q \lor R)</m></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell>using double negation.</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <activity xml:id="act_simplify_complicated_statements">
      <title>Simplifying complicated statements</title>
      <p>
        Negate each statement and use logical equivalences to simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
        State which equivalences you use.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P \lor \neg Q</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\neg P \to Q</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P \land (Q \to R)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_proof_inf">
    <title>\subinference</title>
    <p>
      The primary tool that drives our explanations in proofs are logical inferences.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_logical_infer">
      <title>Logical Inferences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_defn_infer">
              <p>
                For statements <m>S</m> and statement <m>C</m>,
                a <term>logical inference</term>, denoted
                <me>
                  S \implies C
                </me>,
                is a rule saying if we know that statement <m>S</m> is true,
                then we can conclude that statement <m>C</m> is also true.
                For example,
                in <xref ref="exam_truthtable_compound_conditionals"></xref>
                <xref ref="part_truthtable_simplification"/> we proved that <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m> is a tautology.
                Therefore, if we know that <m>S=P \land Q</m> is true,
                we can conclude that <m>C=P</m> is true.
                We write
                <me>
                  P \land Q \implies P
                </me>.
                (This inference <xref ref="thm_logical_infer">is</xref>
                <xref ref="part_thm_infer_simp"/>.)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                An logical inference can also involve multiple statements.
                That is, for statements <m>S_1</m>,
                <m>S_2</m>, <ellipsis/>, <m>S_k</m>, and <m>C</m>.
                The logical inference
                <me>
                  \left. \begin{array}{c} S_1 \\ S_2 \\ \vdots \\ S_k \end{array}  \right\} \implies C
                </me>
                means that if we know that statements <m>S_1</m>, <m>S_2</m>,
                <ellipsis/>, <m>S_k</m> are true,
                then we can conclude that statement <m>C</m> is also true.
                For example,
                if we know that <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q</m> is true,
                then we can conclude that <m>P \land Q</m> is true.
                We write
                <me>
                  \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \\ Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies P \land Q
                </me>.
                (This inference <xref ref="thm_logical_infer">is</xref>
                <xref ref="part_thm_infer_conj"/>.)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A logical inference <m>S \implies C</m> is <term>valid</term>
                if the corresponding conditional statement <m>S \to C</m> is a tautology or,
                equivalently,
                if <m>(S \to C) \equiv \str{T}</m>.
                For example,
                <m>(P \land Q) \implies P</m> is a valid inference because <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m> is a tautology.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      There are five key logical inferences.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_logical_infer">
      <title>Logical inferences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any logical statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> we have the following valid logical inferences.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_thm_infer_simp">
              <p>
                <term>Simplification</term>
                <me>
                  P \land Q \implies P
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_thm_infer_add">
              <p>
                <term>Addition</term>
                <me>
                  P \implies P \lor Q
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_thm_infer_conj">
              <p>
                <term>Conjunction</term>
                <me>
                  \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \\ Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies P \land Q
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_thm_infer_mp">
              <p>
                <term><em>Modus ponens (m.p.)</em></term>
                <me>
                  \left. \begin{array}{cc} P  \\P  \to Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies Q
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_thm_infer_mt">
              <p>
                <term><em>Modus tollens (m.t.)</em></term>
                <me>
                  \left. \begin{array}{cc} \neg Q \\ P \to Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies \neg P
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We explained why simplification and conjunction are valid in <xref ref="defn_logical_infer"></xref>.
      Let's look at why <em>modus ponens</em> is valid.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_mp_valid">
      <title>Why <em>modus ponens</em> is valid</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We proved <em>modus ponens</em>
          in <xref ref="act_proof_logical_equiv"></xref>
          <xref ref="part_proof_mp_using_equiv"/> using equivalences.
          In this example, we look at two different ways to show that
          <em>modus ponens</em> is a valid inference.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Explain in words why <em>modus ponens</em> makes sense.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Suppose we know that <m>P</m> is true and that <m>P \to Q</m> is true.
                    The statement <m>P \to Q</m> promises that if <m>P</m> is true,
                    then <m>Q</m> is guaranteed to be true.
                    Since <m>P</m> is indeed true,
                    it follows that <m>Q</m> is true.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_proof_mp_using_truthtable">
              <p>
                Prove <em>modus ponens</em> is valid using a truth table.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    To prove <em>modus ponens</em> is valid,
                    we need to prove that <m>(P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q</m> is a tautology.
                    The truth table is shown in <xref ref="table_truthtable_mp"></xref>.
                    Notice that the last column is all <c>T</c>,
                    so <m>(P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q</m> is a tautology.
                    Therefore, <em>modus ponens</em> is valid.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_mp">
                  <title>Truth table showing <em>modus ponens</em> is valid <xref ref="exam_mp_valid">for</xref> <xref ref="part_proof_mp_using_truthtable"/></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \land (P \to Q)</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>(P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Let's look at how to use logical inferences to write proofs.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_prove_mt_using_equiv_and_infer">
      <title>Validity of <em>modus tollens</em></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove <em>modus tollens</em> is valid using equivalences and the other inferences.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We want to prove that if <m>P \to Q</m> and <m>\neg Q</m> are each true,
          then <m>\neg P</m> is true.
          As we work through the proof,
          let's number each statement for future reference.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192} <m>P \to Q</m> and \ding{193} <m>\neg Q</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{192} and contraposition <xref ref="thm_cp"/>,
          it follows that \ding{194} <m>\neg Q \to \neg P</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{193}, \ding{194}, and <em>modus ponens</em>,
          it follows that <m>\neg P</m>.
          <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      Your turn to work with logical inferences.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_proofs_equiv_infer">
      <title>Proofs with equivalences and inferences</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Fill in the missing inferences to prove <m>P \land Q \implies P \lor Q</m>.
              <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192} <m>P \land Q</m>.
              By \ding{192} and <fillin/> it follows that \ding{193} <m>P</m>.
              By \ding{193} and <fillin/>,
              it follows that <m>P \lor Q</m>.<nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Fill in the missing conclusions to prove the
              <term>transitivity</term> inference
              <me>
                \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \to Q \\ Q \to R \end{array}  \right\} \implies P \to R
              </me>.
              <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192} <m>P \to Q</m> and \ding{193} <m>Q \to R</m>.
              We will use a direct proof <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"/> to prove <m>P \to R</m>.
              Assume \ding{194} <m>P</m>.
              By \ding{194}, \ding{192}, and <em>modus ponens</em>,
              it follows that \ding{195} <fillin/>.
              By \ding{195}, \ding{193}, and <em>modus ponens</em>,
              it follows that <fillin/>.
              Thus, <m>P \to R</m>.<nbsp/>  <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_proof_equiv_infer_another">
            <p>
              Fill in the missing equivalences,
              inferences, or conclusions to prove
              <me>
                \left. \begin{array}{cc} \neg(Q \lor R) \\ P \to Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies \neg (P \lor R)
              </me>.
              <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192}
              <m>\neg(Q \lor R)</m> and \ding{193} <m>P \to Q</m>.
              By \ding{192} and DeMorgan's Law it follows that \ding{194} <fillin/>.
              By \ding{194} and <fillin/>, it follows that \ding{194} <m>\neg Q</m>.
              By \ding{194}, \ding{193}, and <em>modus tollens</em>,
              it follows that \ding{195} <fillin/>.
              By \ding{194} and <fillin/>,
              it follows that \ding{196} <m>\neg R \land \neg Q</m>.
              By \ding{196} and simplification,
              it follows that \ding{197} <fillin/>.
              By \ding{195}, \ding{197}, and conjunction,
              it follows that \ding{198} <fillin/>.
              By \ding{198} and <fillin/>, it follows that <m>\neg(P \lor R)</m>.
              <nbsp/>  <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Let's look at the proof from <xref ref="act_proofs_equiv_infer"></xref>
      <xref ref="part_proof_equiv_infer_another"/>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_proof_equiv_infer">
      <title>Proof using equivalences and inferences</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Fill in the missing equivalences,
          inferences, or conclusions to prove
          <me>
            \left. \begin{array}{cc} \neg(Q \lor R) \\ P \to Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies \neg (P \lor R)
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192}
          <m>\neg(Q \lor R)</m> and \ding{193} <m>P \to Q</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{192} and DeMorgan's Law it follows that \ding{194} <m>\neg Q \land \neg R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{194} and simplification,
          it follows that \ding{194} <m>\neg Q</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{194}, \ding{193}, and <em>modus tollens</em>,
          it follows that \ding{195} <m>\neg P</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{194} and the commutative property,
          it follows that \ding{196} <m>\neg R \land \neg Q</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{196} and simplification,
          it follows that \ding{197} <m>\neg R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{195}, \ding{197}, and conjunction,
          it follows that \ding{198} <m>\neg P \land \neg R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          By \ding{198} and Demorgan's laws,
          it follows that <m>\neg(P \lor R)</m>.
          <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_logical_equiv">for</xref> \subequiv</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_understanding_equiv_negTF">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For each equivalence, explain words why it is true.
            Recall that by <xref ref="defn_logical_equiv"></xref>
            that two statements are logical equivalent if they have the same truth values and so we can check if one statement is true,
            then so is the other and if one statement is false, then so is the other.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \land P \equiv P</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \land \str{T} \equiv P</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \lor \str{T} \equiv \str{T}</m> Hint: Begin with for the statement <m>P \lor \str{T}</m> to be false,
                  we would need both <ellipsis/>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_assoc">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a truth table to verify the associative property for <m>\land</m>:
            <me>
              P \land (Q \land R) \equiv (P \land Q) \land R
            </me>.
            Include intermediate columns for
            <m>Q \land R</m> and <m>P \land Q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_xor_equiv">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain in words why <m>P \oplus Q \equiv (P \lor Q) \land \neg (P \land Q)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use a truth table to verify that <m>P \oplus Q \equiv (P \lor Q) \land \neg (P \land Q)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_equiv_broken_promise">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Many lists of equivalences omit broken promise because it can be proved from the other equivalences.
            Fill in the missing equivalences in <xref ref="tab_proof_equiv_broken_promise"></xref> to prove broken promise.
          </p>
          <table xml:id="tab_proof_equiv_broken_promise">
            <title>Fill in the blanks to prove broken promise <xref ref="exer_proof_equiv_broken_promise">for</xref></title>
            <tabular>
              <row>
                <cell><em>Proof:</em></cell>
                <cell><m>\neg(P \to Q)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\neg(\neg P \lor Q)</m></cell>
                <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\neg(\neg P) \land \neg Q</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>busing <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>P \land \neg Q</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em> <nbsp/>  <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_equiv_PtoQtoR">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Fill in the missing equivalences in <xref ref="tab_proof_equiv_PtoQtoR"></xref>
            to prove <m>P \to (Q \to R)\equiv (P \land Q) \to R</m>.
          </p>
          <table xml:id="tab_proof_equiv_PtoQtoR">
            <title>Fill in the blanks to prove <m>P \to (Q \to R) \equiv (P \land Q) \to R</m> <xref ref="exer_proof_equiv_PtoQtoR">for</xref></title>
            <tabular>
              <row>
                <cell><em>Proof:</em></cell>
                <cell><m>P \to (Q \to R)</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\neg P \lor (Q \to R)</m></cell>
                <cell><nbsp/>\hspace{.25in}<nbsp/></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\neg P \lor (\neg Q \lor R)</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>(\neg P \lor \neg Q) \lor R</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>\neg(P \land Q) \lor R</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell><m>\equiv</m></cell>
                <cell><m>(P \land Q) \to R</m></cell>
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>using <em>\hspace{1in}</em> <nbsp/>  <nbsp/><m>\Box</m></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_mp_using_equiv">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            This exercise <xref ref="act_proof_logical_equiv">repeats</xref>
            <xref ref="part_proof_mp_using_equiv"/>.
            Fill in the missing equivalences in <xref ref="table_equiv_proof_mp"></xref>
            to prove <m>((P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q) \equiv \str{T}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_simplify_equiv">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use equivalences to simplify <m>(P \land Q) \lor (P \land \neg Q)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_another_equiv_ifthen">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use equivalences to prove <m>\neg(\neg Q \land P) \equiv P \to Q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_logical_equiv">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What it means for two statements to be logically equivalent?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use a truth table to verify that a logical equivalence is valid?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the commutative, associative,
                  and distributive properties tell us?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the double negation equivalence says?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use logical equivalences to prove new logical equivalences?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_equiv_xor">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a truth table to verify the following equivalences involving xor.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Commutative property</term>
                  <m>P \oplus Q \equiv Q \oplus P</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Associative property</term>
                  <m>P \oplus (Q \oplus R) \equiv (P \oplus Q) \oplus R</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sheffer_stroke">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
            the <term>Sheffer stroke</term> (<term>nand</term>),
            denoted <m>P \mid Q</m>, is defined by
            <me>
              P \mid Q \equiv \neg (P \land Q)
            </me>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for <m>P \mid Q</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use equivalences to simplify
                  <m>P \mid \str{T}</m> and <m>P \mid \str{F}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use equivalences to simplify <m>Q \mid Q</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use equivalences to simplify <m>P \mid (Q \mid Q)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_simplify_neg">for</xref> \subneg</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_neg_simple_2vars">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Negate each statement and use logical equivalences to simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
            State which equivalences you use.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \land \neg Q</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\neg P \lor \neg Q</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\neg P \to \neg Q</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_neg_complicated_and_or">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Negate each statement and use logical equivalences to simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
            State which equivalences you use.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \lor (Q \land R)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(P \land R) \lor (Q \land \neg R)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_neg_ifthen">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Negate each statement and use logical equivalences to simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
            State which equivalences you use.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \to (Q \lor \neg R)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(P \to Q) \land (R \to \neg Q)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_simplify_neg">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What DeMorgan's laws say?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the broken promise equivalence says?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to simplify negations using equivalences?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_negating_biconditional_using_equiv">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Recall that <m>P \leftrightarrow Q \equiv (P \to Q) \land (Q \to P)</m>.
                  Negate <m>P \leftrightarrow Q</m> and use logical equivalences to simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
                  State which equivalences you use.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Recall that <m>P \oplus Q \equiv (P \lor Q) \land \neg (P \land Q)</m>.
                  Negate <m>P \oplus Q</m> and use logical equivalences to simplify your negation so that there are no negation signs in front of parentheses.
                  State which equivalences you use.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What do you notice?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_proof_inf">for</xref> \subinference</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_PandQimpliesQ">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Fill in the missing conclusions to prove <m>P \land Q \implies Q</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192} <m>P \land Q</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{192} and the commutative property it follows that \ding{193} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{193} and simplification,
            it follows that <fillin/>.<nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_complicated_infer">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Fill in the missing inferences to prove the inference
            <me>
              \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \\ P \to Q \\ P \to R \end{array}  \right\} \implies Q \land R
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192} <m>P</m>, \ding{193} <m>P \to Q</m> and \ding{194} <m>P \to R</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{192}, \ding{193}, and <fillin/>, it follows that \ding{195} <m>Q</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{192}, \ding{194}, and <fillin/>, it follows that \ding{196} <m>R</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{195}, \ding{196}, and <fillin/>,
            it follows that <m>Q \land R</m>.<nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_doublemp_equiv_infer">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use equivalences and inferences to prove
                  <me>
                    \left. \begin{array}{c} P \\ P \to Q \\ Q \to R \end{array}  \right\} \implies R
                  </me>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use equivalences and inferences from our lists to prove
                  <me>
                    \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \land Q \\ P \to R \\ Q \to S \end{array}  \right\} \implies R \land S
                  </me>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_or_form_mp">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain in your own words why <m>\left. \begin{array}{cc} P \lor Q \\ \neg P \end{array} \right\} \implies Q</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Fill in the missing equivalences and inferences to prove <m>\left. \begin{array}{cc} P \lor Q \\ \neg P \end{array} \right\} \implies Q</m>.
                  <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192} <m>P\lor Q</m> and \ding{193} <m>\neg P</m>.
                  By <fillin/> it follows from \ding{192} that <m>\neg (\neg P) \lor Q</m>.
                  By <fillin/>, it follows that <m>\neg P \to Q</m>.
                  We know <m>\neg P</m> from \ding{193}, so by <fillin/> it follows that <m>Q</m> <m>\Box</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_equiv_infer_proof_by_cases">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Fill in the missing equivalences,
            inferences, or conclusions,
            to prove the inference that justifies proof by cases ( <xref ref="pff_cases"></xref>.
            <me>
              \left. \begin{array}{c} P \lor Q \\ P \to R \\ Q \to R \end{array}  \right \} \implies R
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192}
            <m>P \lor Q</m>, \ding{193} <m>P \to R</m>,
            and \ding{194} <m>Q \to R</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{193}, \ding{194}, and conjunction it follows that \ding{195} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{195} and implication (twice),
            it follows that \ding{196} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{196} and the commutative property (twice),
            it follows that \ding{197} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{197} and the distributive property,
            it follows that \ding{198} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{198} and the commutative property,
            it follows that \ding{199} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{199} and Demorgan's law,
            it follows that \ding{200} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{199} and implication,
            it follows that \ding{201} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{201}, \ding{192}, and <fillin/> it follows that <m>R</m>.
            <nbsp/> <nbsp/><m>\Box</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_infer_random">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Fill in the missing equivalences and inferences to prove
            <me>
              \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \land Q  \\ \neg(\neg R \land P) \end{array}  \right\} \implies P \land R
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192}
            <m>P\land Q</m> and \ding{193} <m>\neg(\neg R \land P)</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By <fillin/> it follows from \ding{193} that <m>\neg (\neg R) \lor \neg P</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By <fillin/>, it follows that <m>R \lor \neg P</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By <fillin/>, it follows that <m>\neg P \lor R</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By <fillin/>, it follows that <m>P \to R</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By <fillin/>, it follows from \ding{192} that <m>P</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By <fillin/>, it follows that <m>R</m>.
            <m>\Box</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_infer_random2">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the inference
            <me>
              \left. \begin{array}{cc} P \to \neg Q  \\ R \to (P \land Q) \end{array}  \right\} \implies \neg R
            </me>.
            Fill in the missing steps to prove it,
            using the equivalences and inferences given.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Proof.</em> Assume \ding{192}
            <m>P \to \neg Q</m> and \ding{193} <m>R \to (P \land Q)</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{192} and implication,
            it follows that \ding{194} <fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{193} and DeMorgan's laws,
            it follows that \ding{195}<fillin/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            By \ding{193}, \ding{195}, <em>modus tollens</em>,
            it follows that <fillin/>.
            <m>\Box</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_infer_contradiction">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> Use equivalences and inferences from our lists to prove
            <me>
              \left. \begin{array}{cc} \neg P \to Q \\ \neg P \to \neg Q \end{array}  \right\} \implies P
            </me>
            which is the inference that justifies proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/>.
            Hint: Start with conjunction.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_logical_inference">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What a logical inference is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use a truth table to verify a logical inference?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What <em>modus ponens</em> and <em>modus ponens</em>
                  say and how to use them in a proof?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why the simplification, conjunction,
                  and addition inferences are valid?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use logical equivalences and logical inferences to prove new logical inferences?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_understanding_equiv_negTF"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>P \land P</m> is true, then <m>P</m> is true and <m>P</m> is true.
            That is, <m>P</m> is true.
            On the other hand, if <m>P \land P</m> is false,
            then <m>P</m> is false or <m>P</m> is false.
            That is, <m>P</m> is false.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Follow the format from (a).
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Follow the hint.
            It should never be false.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_truthtable_assoc"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Your truth table should have seven columns:
        <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>, <m>Q \land R</m>,
        <m>P \land (Q \land R)</m>, <m>P \land Q</m>,
        and <m>(P \land Q) \land R</m>.
        Your truth table should have eight rows.
        The fifth column and the seventh column should match.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_xor_equiv"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: If <m>P \oplus Q</m> is true,
            then <m>P</m> is true or <m>Q</m> is true, but not both.
            Since at least one of <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> is true,
            it follows that <m>P \lor Q</m> is true.
            Since not both are true, it follows that <m>P \land Q</m> is false.
            That is, <m>\neg(P \land Q)</m> is true.
            Thus, <m>(P \lor Q) \land \neg(P \land Q)</m> is true.
            Now explain what happens if <m>P \oplus Q</m> is false.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your truth table should have seven columns <m>P</m>,
            <m>Q</m>, <m>P \oplus Q</m>, <m>P \lor Q</m>, <m>P \land Q</m>,
            <m>\neg(P \land Q)</m>, and <m>(P \lor Q) \land \neg (P \land Q)</m>.
            Your truth table should have four rows.
            The third and seventh columns should match.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_equiv_broken_promise"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The three reasons, in some order,
        are DeMorgan's laws, double negation, and implication.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_equiv_PtoQtoR"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The proof uses the associative property, DeMorgan's laws,
        and implication.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_mp_using_equiv"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The first three reasons are, in some order,
        the distributive property, implication, and negation.
        Other reasons used include DeMorgan's laws and identity.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_simplify_equiv"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Start with the distributive property to get
        <me>
          (P \land Q) \lor (P \land \neg Q) \equiv P \land (Q \lor \neg Q)
        </me>.
        Next, use negation.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_neg_simple_2vars"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The answer is <m>\neg P \lor Q</m> Show the steps of your work and state which equivalences you use.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer has no negations.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Use broken promise.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_neg_ifthen"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The answer is <m>P \land (\neg Q \land R)</m>.
            Show the steps of your work and state which equivalences you use.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer includes <m>\lor</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_PandQimpliesQ"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        <m>Q \land P</m>, <m>Q</m>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_complicated_infer"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The proof uses conjunction and <em>modus ponens</em>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_doublemp_equiv_infer"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The proof uses <em>modus ponens</em> twice.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Use simplification, but be careful.
            It says <m>P \land Q \implies P</m>.
            If you later want to conclude <m>Q</m> instead,
            you need to use the commutative property first.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_equiv_infer_proof_by_cases"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The first blank should say <m>(P \to R) \land (Q \to R)</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_infer_random2"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The second blank is <m>\neg(P \land Q)</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_infer_contradiction"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Use conjunction to get <m>(\neg P \to Q) \land (\neg P \to \neg Q)</m>.
        Next, use implication (twice), double negation (twice),
        the distributive property, negation, and then identity.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>